ation ban. By charting the complex circulation of people, property, and print from the Pacific Rim to the Black Atlantic, Racial Reconstruction sheds new light on comparative racialization in America, and illuminates how slavery and Reconstruction influenced the histories of Chinese immigration to the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryx19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryy19th century. 0aAmerican prose literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aAmerican prose literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChinesexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aChinesezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEmigration and immigration lawxHistoryxUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aLabor movement in literature. 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 0aWorking class in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479868001.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479899043423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479899043/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles